# DSG Inflation Pipeline — Design Decisions & Team Summary

## 1. Dataset Selection

We had two candidate datasets:

### Dataset A: `pakistan_economic_indicators_2000_2025.csv`
- **26 rows** (2000–2025), **31 columns**
- Columns include: `gdp_usd_bn`, `gdp_growth_pct`, `gdp_per_capita_usd`, `inflation_cpi_pct`, `unemployment_pct`, `remittances_usd_bn`, `exports_usd_bn`, `imports_usd_bn`, `trade_balance_usd_bn`, `forex_reserves_usd_bn`, `policy_rate_pct`, `pkr_per_usd`, `public_debt_gdp_pct`, `current_account_usd_bn`, `fdi_inflows_usd_bn`, `population_mn`, `literacy_rate_pct`, `agriculture_gdp_pct`, `services_gdp_pct`, `industry_gdp_pct`, `tax_revenue_gdp_pct`, `mobile_per_100`, `imf_program_active`, `key_events` (text), plus derived ratio/category columns
- Contains categorical/text columns (`key_events`, `gdp_growth_category`, `inflation_category`, `decade`) that would need encoding
- Dollar-denominated values (GDP in USD billions, exports in USD billions)

### Dataset B: `Data for Inflation Forecasting in Pakistan.csv` ✅ CHOSEN
- **36 rows** (1986–2021), **10 columns**
- Columns: `Year`, `Inflation`, `Exchange Rate`, `GDPGrowth`, `Unemployment`, `BroadMoney`, `Exports`, `Imports`, `Oilrents`, `remittances`
- All numeric, no categorical columns, no text fields — clean for direct pipeline use
- Local-currency / percentage-based values (Broad Money in PKR billions, rates in %)

### Why Dataset B was chosen:
- **Longer time span** (36 years vs. 26) — more annual anchor points for cubic spline interpolation, producing smoother and more reliable monthly estimates
- **Simpler, cleaner structure** — all 10 columns are continuous numeric values ready for interpolation and normalization. Dataset A has text columns (`key_events`), binary flags (`imf_program_active`), and categorical labels that would need special handling
- **Focused feature set** — 10 well-chosen macro indicators vs. 31 columns where many are derived ratios of each other (e.g., `exports_usd_bn` AND `exports_gdp_pct`), which would introduce multicollinearity
- **Better for DSG demonstration** — the goal is to demonstrate distributed optimization, not to maximize prediction accuracy. A clean 10-feature dataset is more interpretable and easier to validate
- **Dataset A's trade-off:** It has more recent data (up to 2025) and richer context (IMF programs, policy rates), but the categorical columns, dollar-denominated values, and redundant derived columns would add preprocessing complexity without benefiting the DSG simulation

